        <body>
            <pb n="1"/>
            <p rend="align(right)"><placeName>St. Thomas</placeName>, <date>1<hi rend="sup">st</hi>
                    Jan. 1863</date>.</p>
            <p>
                <addressee>Rev. Isaac Leeser</addressee>
            </p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">
                <placeName>Philadelphia</placeName>
            </p>
            <p rend="indent(2)">Dear Sir,</p>
            <p rend="indent(3)">I wrote you on <date>23rd</date><lb/> ult. since when I have been
                placed in posses<lb/>sion of yours of <date>8<hi rend="sup">th</hi></date> ult. The
                subject being<lb/> an unpleasant one, I reply thereto only to cor<lb/>rect any
                erroneous impressions which may<lb/> have been formed on your mind. If my
                fa<lb/>ther has mentioned any names I would assure<lb/> you that the small balance
                which was due<lb/> me has been repaid, the delay being but a<lb/> temporary
                indulgence which on my part, I<lb/> was desirous of shewing, therefore quite a
                pri<lb/>vate affair. Then Sterling being the only<lb/> remittance none made to the
                    <placeName>States</placeName>, I had<lb/> to include your dues in a Bill I sent
                to <placeName>Bos<lb/>ton</placeName>, sending you another for the amt. With<lb/>
                10% dis. while if the first realize the rate</p>
            <pb n="2"/>
            <p>non quoted, I shall make sufficiently on the lat<lb/>ter to repay myself for any
                trifle I may have open.<lb/> I trust that this explanation will satisfy you,<lb/> as
                it should; and that you will excuse any<lb/>thing unpleasant in my Father's letter
                for you<lb/> must know that but for his unfortunate mal<lb/>ady which you have
                noticed, he could not have<lb/> mentioned anything of the kind. We have already<lb/>
                had reason to complain that more care should<lb/> not have been taken to prevent his
                communica<lb/>ting with persons abroad without his letters pas<lb/>sing thro' the
                Dr's hands. But I am sorry that<lb/> you should call the distribution of a few
                copies<lb/> of a religious work, a kindness, or that you shld.<lb/> find therein any
                reason to regret my being person<lb/>ally unknown to you. You remind me that<lb/> I
                was the one who took the liberty of commencing<lb/> the correspondence.</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">I would thank you for your kind sympathy<lb/> and good wishes,
                remaining, Rev. Sir,</p>
            <p rend="indent(10)">Yours truly</p>
            <p rend="indent(11)">
                <persName role="author">D. M. Pizal</persName>
            </p>
        </body>
